{"source_key":"sha256-b4cec238995b260ac54aae4fdce1a71d","record_index":281,"record_hash":"sha256:ed89a7f9c00fb99536b32205b12edd3be6d7f39bd4e1a5fa5c4a79c6fe07a3ba","timestamp":"2026-05-31T12:22:31.169Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 302faf\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 556\nOutput:\n# Agentlog Local-First Publishing\n\n## Intent\n\nMake `but-agentlog` private by default.\n\nCaptured agent sessions should stay local unless the user explicitly publishes\nthem. A reviewer-facing Agent Trail page should only exist for metadata the user\nhas chosen to share, or for users who have opted into sharing agentlogs by\ndefault.\n\n## Next Agent Brief\n\nUse this as scope, not a full implementation plan.\n\nStart by inspecting whether `git-meta-lib` already has a safe key move / rename\nprimitive. If not, decide whether the primitive belongs upstream in\n`[REDACTED:path]` or narrowly inside `but-agentlog`.\n\nKeep the implementation contained:\n\n- default new captures to local-only\n- add explicit publish by branch/review/change\n- publish whole sessions\n- keep Agent Trail consuming only published metadata\n- avoid broad policy systems or fake extensibility\n\n## Why\n\nToday capture and publish are effectively coupled. The agent hook records a\nsession, then `but-agentlog` silently runs metadata sync. That means a user who\nhas GitMeta sync configured can publish every captured agentlog without taking a\nseparate sharing action.\n\nThat is too leaky for normal work. A user may be:\n\n- exploring private customer metrics or internal stats on a public repository\n- using an agent for sensitive investigation before deciding what belongs in a PR\n- not ready to share a branch's agent context yet\n- philosophically fine with local capture but not automatic propagation\n\nThe safer default is local-first capture plus explicit publish.\n\nThis is consent